 {"id":"br-r42-c1-01","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] min_edge_cover crashed with fnx matching_algorithm","description":"fnx.min_edge_cover delegated to nx when matching_algorithm was supplied, but the delegation wrapper (_call_networkx_for_parity) converts G to an nx.Graph before calling, and then nx calls matching_algorithm(converted_G). If the caller passed a fnx matching function (e.g. fnx.max_weight_matching) it received an nx.Graph and raised TypeError: expected Graph, DiGraph, MultiGraph, or MultiDiGraph. Rewrote min_edge_cover in Python as a literal port of nx's algorithm so the supplied matching_algorithm is called with G directly.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","updated_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","close_reason":"Fixed. Verified default path, matching_algorithm=fnx.max_weight_matching, bipartite dict-returning path, and raise-on-directed/multigraph all match nx."}
 {"id":"br-r42-c2-01","title":"REVIEW: [MEDIUM] is_eulerian returned False on single-self-loop graph","description":"fnx.is_eulerian forwarded to the Rust _raw_is_eulerian, which returned False for Graph([(0,0)]). nx returns True because a self-loop contributes +2 to degree (even) and the graph is connected — the classic Königsberg criterion is satisfied. Added a Python branch for graphs with <=1 node that walks degrees directly (including self-loop contributions) and returns True when all degrees are even; 2+ node case still uses the Rust fast path. Verified: self-loop-only Graph, empty, K3, P4, two-self-loops MultiGraph, and directed self-loop all match nx.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","updated_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","close_reason":"Fixed: Python guard for n<=1 catches the self-loop case; larger graphs unchanged."}
